{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01SYFfGfmQuL87D58cSf7QEx","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me carefully validate the knowledge file against the source file by going through each check.\n\n**V1: Omission Check**\n\nLet me read through the source carefully and compare with the knowledge file sections.\n\nSource sections:\n1. 出力ライブラリ(同期応答メッセージ送信処理)の構造とテスト範囲\n2. テストの実施方法\n3. テストデータの書き方 (subsection)\n   - 要求電文の期待値および、返却する応答電文（レスポンスメッセージ）の準備\n   - 電文表の書式定義 (implied)\n   - 要求電文の記載例\n4. 障害系のテスト\n5. テスト結果検証\n\nNow I'm checking each section against what's documented. For the first section on the output library structure and test scope, the source covers request ID-based testing, notes about request IDs as unique identifiers for external system functions (distinct from screen/batch IDs), definitions of request and response messages, and the test flow outline.\n\nThe test framework has some distinctive features worth noting—test data is straightforward to write using Excel formatted according to external interface design specifications, and the superclass handles message synchronous transmission testing so individual test code isn't needed.\n\nFor the implementation method section, I'm seeing that it follows the same testing approach as screen online processing and batch processing, with specific guidance on test class writing and preparation data methods referenced elsewhere. This section focuses only on the unique implementation aspects specific to this framework.\n\nTest data files follow a simple naming convention—they go in the same directory as the test source code with the same name but different file extension, with details in the how_to_write_excel reference.\n\nNow looking at how test data should be structured: each request ID maps to request and response message headers and body formats with data definitions, and the expectedMessage and responseMessage groups are linked by grou